Election draws near

Tick-tock, tick-tock. The countdown to the Nov. 8 mid-presi-
dential term elections is upon us. Many politicians and spin-
doctors are calling this election the most important of a genera-
tion. Elections usually tend to get over-hyped as they approach,
but this year’s elections very likely deserve the attention.

The stakes are control of the House of Representatives and the
Senate. Both are currently in the hands of the Democrats and
have been for eight years. In the Senate, the Democrats hold a
slim 56-44 majority. The Republicans would need to capture
seven of the 35 seats being contested to regain the majority they
last held in 1986. One of those crucial races is the Pennsylvania
senatorial race between Senator Harris Wofford and
Congressman Rick Santorum. Current polls say that this race is
too close to call.

It is generally agreed that it would be harder for the
Republicans to pull off a win in the House. They would need to
gain and additional 40 out of the 435 seats at stake to win a
majority for the first time in 40 years.

7 With less than two weeks to go, polls are predicting large
Republican gains. However, there have been signs of a
Democratic comeback.

Massachusetts Sen. Edward Kennedy, who has been in one of
the year’s toughest races, opened up an 18-point lead over
Republican challenger Mitt Romney in the latest poll. Also,
California Democrat Diane Feinstein seems to have solidified a
small lead over challenger Michael Huffington.

The White House has finally eased its way into the campaign.
Democrats’ avoidance of President Clinton has been an issue of
ridicule over the last month, but Clinton just returned from cam-
paigning for Democratic candidates in the‘ Pacific Northwest
before leaving for the Middle East. Vice-President Al Gore has
been outspoken in his attacks of the Republicans. “The issue
before us is not just who gains seats, but whether a deliberate,
protracted, reckless strategy of partisan paralysis will be permit-
ted to stop our counfry’s progress,” Gore said recently. He has,
not surprisingly, predicted that the tide is turning in favor of the
Democrats.

However, those whose profession it is to cast the political
future tell a different story. Both Democrats and Republicans

agree that there will be significant gains by the Republicans; the .

only question is how much. Many Republicans, such as strate-
gist Bill Kristol and former Tennessee Gov. Lamar Alexander,
predict a Republican majority in both the House and the Senate.
However, Republican consultant Ed Rollins predicts a
Republican majority only in the Senate, with a 32-seat gain in
the House. C

Democratic pollsters are being cautiously optimistic, believ-
ing they can still hold onto narrow majorities in both houses.

Finally, before anyone cites this year’s election as the doom of
Clinton’s presidency, it should be noted that it is customary for
the incumbent president’s party to loss ground in Congress dur-
ing mid-terrn elections.

