Animal research

Last Friday was National
Biomedical Research Day.
Research science has fallen
under attack by a variety of
groups who bemoan its short-
comings or declare it worthless.
These groups are grossly misin-
formed.

We all know the litany of dis-
ease laid to rest by research sci-
ence. Polio, small pox and
countless other ills, once fright-
ening reality, are now the stuff
of history. But what has bio-
medical research done lately?
This year saw breakthroughs in
understanding the cause of
Alzheimer’s, Muscular
Dystrophy and Cystic Fibrosis.
In the last case, identiﬁcation of
the defective gene provided the
basis for gene transfer research
which will save thousands of
lives. Within the last month, two
major advances were realized.
Researchers have identified the
BRCAI gene, known to place
women at risk of developing
early onset breast and ovarian
cancer, while researchers here at
the University of Pittsburgh
uncovered a possible trigger of
diabetes mellitus. Knowing the
cause means knowing how to
screen for, and eventually cure,
the disease. ’

So the next time someone
claims that we have not beneﬁt-
ed from biomedical research, or
that research scientists simply
abuse laboratory animals, ask
them where they would be with-

out it. Very likely, the answer is
worse off.

